00:17:48,479 --> 00:17:52,958
Mr President, I'm not interested
in using Ellie to further my career.

268
00:17:53,118 --> 00:17:55,198
What do you know about E.L.E.?

269
00:17:57,319 --> 00:18:00,798
I know you should have picked a
better cover story than a sick wife.

270
00:18:00,838 --> 00:18:01,718
See?

271
00:18:01,798 --> 00:18:03,718
What did I tell you?

272
00:18:06,039 --> 00:18:07,839
We'd always thought
the deadline for going public

273
00:18:07,880 --> 00:18:09,879
was the publication of the budget,

274
00:18:09,959 --> 00:18:12,119
since we've spent more
money than we can hide.

275
00:18:12,199 --> 00:18:14,439
The budget comes out in 2 weeks.

276
00:18:14,639 --> 00:18:18,919
I don't suppose I could convince
you to sit on this for 2 weeks.

277
00:18:19,519 --> 00:18:22,760
No such thing as 2 weeks
in the news business.

278
00:18:22,839 --> 00:18:26,159
And I can't appeal to your sense
of what's in the nation's best interest?

279
00:18:26,999 --> 00:18:30,679
I always thought the truth was
in the nation's best interest.

280
00:18:33,319 --> 00:18:35,359
Entrekin:
You want to hold her?

281
00:18:35,440 --> 00:18:39,479
What if we go public in 48 hours?

282
00:18:39,560 --> 00:18:41,279
Now that's doable, isn't it?

283
00:18:41,359 --> 00:18:43,159
Entrekin: That would be very difficult, Mr President.

284
00:18:43,239 --> 00:18:46,319
Morton, if she knows, how long can it be

285
00:18:46,399 --> 00:18:49,559
before CNN or the Post breaks the story?

286
00:18:49,639 --> 00:18:53,640
This was never gonna be a secret
as long as you wanted it to be.

287
00:18:55,280 --> 00:18:56,800
Give us 2 days, Ms Lerner.

288
00:18:56,879 --> 00:19:00,000
You'll get second row, centre, at
the White House press conference.

289
00:19:00,159 --> 00:19:02,200
Now, from what I know of your
career, that's a promotion.

290
00:19:02,280 --> 00:19:03,240
I want exclusivity.

291
00:19:03,319 --> 00:19:05,279
Now, listen, young lady.

292
00:19:05,880 --> 00:19:08,159
This is a presidential favor.

293
00:19:08,641 --> 00:19:11,320
I'm letting you go because
I don't want another headache.

294
00:19:11,521 --> 00:19:15,840
And I'm trusting you because I know
what this can do for your career.

295
00:19:15,880 --> 00:19:18,680
It might seem that we have each other
over the same barrel, Ms Lerner,

296
00:19:18,680 --> 00:19:21,400
but it just seems that way.

297
00:19:26,481 --> 00:19:26,721
I want--

298
00:19:26,801 --> 00:19:28,121
Want?

299
00:19:31,041 --> 00:19:32,841
May l...

300
00:19:32,921 --> 00:19:35,680
May I have the first question?

301
00:19:35,761 --> 00:19:38,880
We'll see you Tuesday,
Ms Lerner.

302
00:20:00,601 --> 00:20:03,641
Come on, come on.

303
00:20:14,442 --> 00:20:16,762
E.L.E., E.L.E.

304
00:20:24,362 --> 00:20:25,521
Paleontology?

305
00:20:25,601 --> 00:20:26,881
Paleontology?

306
00:20:26,962 --> 00:20:29,802
What's paleontology
have to do with anything?

307
00:20:29,882 --> 00:20:31,083
Come on.

308
00:20:51,001 --> 00:20:52,361
Beth: Hey.

309
00:20:52,442 --> 00:20:53,522
Hey.

310
00:20:53,601 --> 00:20:54,642
Look who's working late.

311
00:20:54,721 --> 00:20:56,361
How's Rittenhouse going?

312
00:20:56,442 --> 00:20:57,881
No sign of the wife yet.

313
00:20:57,962 --> 00:20:59,161
Is she missing?

314
00:20:59,241 --> 00:21:00,321
No. We're still working on it.

315
00:21:00,401 --> 00:21:01,322
We'll get there.

316
00:21:01,402 --> 00:21:02,722
I know, it's a dull story.

317
00:21:02,802 --> 00:21:04,683
Next time we'll get you
something more exciting.

318
00:21:04,762 --> 00:21:06,762
Great.

319
00:21:06,842 --> 00:21:08,282
Are you OK?

320
00:21:08,362 --> 00:21:10,642
- Yeah.
- Want to come to dinner with us?

321
00:21:10,722 --> 00:21:15,522
- I can't.  I can't.  I got my plans.
- Well, OK. We'll see you tomorrow.

322
00:21:25,363 --> 00:21:26,522
Jenny: Thank you.

323
00:21:30,642 --> 00:21:32,602
Ah, here she is.

324
00:21:32,682 --> 00:21:34,203
Jenny.

325
00:21:34,284 --> 00:21:36,043
Hello.

326
00:21:37,683 --> 00:21:39,163
Hi, Chloe.

327
00:21:39,244 --> 00:21:40,083
Waiter: Would you like
some champagne, miss?

328
00:21:40,163 --> 00:21:42,923
Martini...big.

329
00:21:46,003 --> 00:21:47,803
I missed you.

330
00:21:47,883 --> 00:21:50,963
I mean we missed you yesterday.

331
00:21:51,043 --> 00:21:53,883
I must say, I'm...

332
00:21:53,962 --> 00:21:55,643
I'm disturbed that you didn't come

333
00:21:55,722 --> 00:21:56,603
to our wedding.

334
00:21:56,682 --> 00:21:58,163
Jason, you promised.

335
00:21:58,243 --> 00:21:59,763
I know I promised,

336
00:21:59,842 --> 00:22:01,163
but it was a beautiful event,

337
00:22:01,242 --> 00:22:02,403
and I missed her.

338
00:22:02,482 --> 00:22:03,722
You should have been there.

339
00:22:03,803 --> 00:22:05,724
The twins, they were
running around like mad

340
00:22:05,803 --> 00:22:07,683
and throwing flowers.

341
00:22:07,764 --> 00:22:09,483
It was wonderful, especially Emma.

342
00:22:09,564 --> 00:22:11,723
You know, the little one.
She loves you.

343
00:22:11,803 --> 00:22:13,003
It was beautiful.

344
00:22:13,083 --> 00:22:14,123
She missed you, too.

345
00:22:14,203 --> 00:22:16,683
All right.

346
00:22:17,163 --> 00:22:19,603
This is from us for you.

347
00:22:23,684 --> 00:22:26,043
Are you not going to open it?

348
00:22:42,684 --> 00:22:44,925
I knew she wouldn't...

349
00:22:45,004 --> 00:22:48,245
You can exchange them
if you don't like them.

350
00:22:48,324 --> 00:22:50,165
Jenny, I know this is hard.

351
00:22:50,244 --> 00:22:52,164
I just want you to be happy.

352
00:22:52,244 --> 00:22:53,284
Happy.

353
00:22:53,364 --> 00:22:54,884
Well,

354
00:22:54,964 --> 00:22:58,564
I would like to propose
a toast to happiness

355
00:22:58,644 --> 00:22:59,724
and to--

356
00:23:11,204 --> 00:23:14,165
Are we going to have an evening or not?

357
00:23:14,245 --> 00:23:16,244
Jenny, I know that you hate me.

358
00:23:16,325 --> 00:23:17,884
I know that you have terrible things

359
00:23:17,965 --> 00:23:19,284
that you want to say to me.

360
00:23:19,365 --> 00:23:21,644
You have to get over it.

361
00:23:21,724 --> 00:23:23,284
Life goes on.

362
00:23:23,844 --> 00:23:25,565
Jenny: Life goes on? OK.

363
00:23:25,645 --> 00:23:26,805
[Laughing]

364
00:23:28,325 --> 00:23:29,765
What's so funny?

365
00:23:29,845 --> 00:23:31,485
Life...

366
00:23:33,645 --> 00:23:36,605
We'll see.

367
00:23:36,685 --> 00:23:39,725
What's so funny about "life goes on"?

368
00:23:39,805 --> 00:23:41,125
Life going on?

369
00:23:41,204 --> 00:23:43,965
I don't think it's funny that life goes on.

370
00:23:44,046 --> 00:23:47,965
Dad, you need to get
back together with Mom.

371
00:23:48,245 --> 00:23:52,765
She's all alone in the world,
and she needs you right now OK?

372
00:23:54,726 --> 00:23:55,805
Jenny.

373
00:23:56,485 --> 00:23:57,685
I just got married.

374
00:23:57,766 --> 00:24:01,565
I know, I know, and I'm sorry.
Chloe, this has nothing to do with you.

375
00:24:01,605 --> 00:24:05,085
Jason: Well, it has to do something
for me, for Christ's sake.

376
00:24:05,165 --> 00:24:06,285
This is insane.

377
00:24:06,365 --> 00:24:11,085
- I have to apologize for my daughter.
- That is not your fault.

378
00:24:11,165 --> 00:24:12,565
I'm sorry.  I have to go.

379
00:24:13,645 --> 00:24:16,206
I know you think I'm a bad person.
I'm really not.

380
00:24:16,246 --> 00:24:18,006
And I don't hate you.

381
00:24:18,086 --> 00:24:20,605
I just--I gotta go.

382
00:24:23,566 --> 00:24:26,365
[Reporters All Talking At Once
in Different Languages]

383
00:24:47,807 --> 00:24:50,367
'Cause for her, it doesn't--
Excuse me.

384
00:24:50,447 --> 00:24:52,207
Jenny. Hey.

385
00:24:52,287 --> 00:24:54,726
What are you doing here?

386
00:24:54,807 --> 00:24:56,047
Uh, yeah.

387
00:24:56,126 --> 00:24:57,486
Did Stuart send you here
without telling me?

388
00:24:57,567 --> 00:24:59,047
No.

389
00:24:59,126 --> 00:25:01,807
If Stuart thinks he can push
me out of the White House--

390
00:25:01,886 --> 00:25:03,806
Ms Lerner.  Hi, Beth.

391
00:25:03,887 --> 00:25:04,886
Right this way.

392
00:25:04,967 --> 00:25:07,006
I've got you right down here.

393
00:25:12,807 --> 00:25:14,047
Excuse me, please.

394
00:25:15,886 --> 00:25:17,006
OK.

395
00:25:17,086 --> 00:25:19,047
He'll find you for the first question.

396
00:25:19,127 --> 00:25:20,447
Then you're on your own.

397
00:25:21,967 --> 00:25:23,487
Hey, how are you?

398
00:25:25,087 --> 00:25:26,447
<i>Press Secretary:
Ladies and gentlemen.</i>

399
00:25:26,727 --> 00:25:29,967
<i>Ladies and gentlemen, please</i>

400
00:25:30,087 --> 00:25:33,126
<i>The president will begin
by addressing the nation.</i>

401
00:25:33,207 --> 00:25:35,887
Please hold your questions
until he's finished his remarks.

402
00:25:35,968 --> 00:25:37,048
Ladies and gentlemen,

403
00:25:37,127 --> 00:25:39,047
the President of the United States.

404
00:25:42,487 --> 00:25:43,887
Hello, everybody.

405
00:25:43,967 --> 00:25:45,407
- Mr President.
- Hello.

406
00:25:45,487 --> 00:25:47,648
Man: 10 seconds, Mr President.

407
00:25:49,087 --> 00:25:50,648
5, 4.

408
00:25:53,048 --> 00:25:54,208
Good evening.

409
00:25:55,688 --> 00:25:58,288
A few minutes ago
the United States ambassadors

410
00:25:58,367 --> 00:25:59,408
to every country in the world

411
00:25:59,488 --> 00:26:02,688
told the leaders of those nations
what I am about to tell you.

412
00:26:03,047 --> 00:26:05,527
It's a bit complicated,
so it will take some time,

413
00:26:05,608 --> 00:26:07,768
so I hope
you will bear with me,

414
00:26:07,847 --> 00:26:09,968
hear what I have to say.

415
00:26:10,047 --> 00:26:12,127
A little over a year ago,

416
00:26:12,208 --> 00:26:16,448
2 American astronomers,
Marcus Wolfand Leo Biederman,

417
00:26:16,527 --> 00:26:19,007
working on a mountain top in Arizona...

418
00:26:20,288 --> 00:26:21,487
Nobody say anything.

419
00:26:21,567 --> 00:26:23,088
<i>saw something in the night sky</i>

420
00:26:23,169 --> 00:26:24,528
<i>that caused them great concern.</i>

421
00:26:24,608 --> 00:26:26,448
<i>A comet.</i>

422
00:26:27,048 --> 00:26:30,008
<i>But the comet was, well...</i>

423
00:26:30,488 --> 00:26:34,008
There was a remote possibility
that the comet was on a path

424
00:26:34,088 --> 00:26:37,047
that could bring it into
direct contact with the Earth.

425
00:26:37,128 --> 00:26:38,968
[Crowd Murmurs]

426
00:26:39,769 --> 00:26:40,329
Now...

427
00:26:40,409 --> 00:26:43,489
we get hit all the time
by rocks and meteors,

428
00:26:43,569 --> 00:26:46,688
some of them the size of cars,
some no bigger than your hand.

429
00:26:46,769 --> 00:26:49,728
But the comet we discovered
is the size of New York City.

430
00:26:49,808 --> 00:26:52,968
From the north side
of Central Park to the Battery.

431
00:26:53,049 --> 00:26:55,970
About 7 miles long.

432
00:26:56,049 --> 00:26:57,849
Put another way,

433
00:26:58,089 --> 00:27:01,009
this comet is larger than Mount Everest.

434
00:27:01,089 --> 00:27:04,689
It weighs 500 billion tons.

435
00:27:04,769 --> 00:27:07,169
Now, chances are...

436
00:27:07,249 --> 00:27:10,689
Astrophysicists, geologists
and climatologists.

437
00:27:10,769 --> 00:27:12,049
Where the hell
is Science?

438
00:27:12,129 --> 00:27:14,849
Check with Tokyo, Tel Aviv.
I want everybody.

439
00:27:14,929 --> 00:27:16,568
The Hale-Bopp stand-ups.

440
00:27:16,649 --> 00:27:18,569
Graphics!  I need graphics!

441
00:27:18,649 --> 00:27:21,169
<i>President Beck: Comets begin
far out in space.</i>

442
00:27:21,248 --> 00:27:22,488
<i>They're what's left over</i>

443
00:27:22,569 --> 00:27:24,368
<i>from the creation
of the solar system</i>

444
00:27:24,449 --> 00:27:27,409
<i>after the planets were formed
billions of years ago.</i>

445
00:27:27,490 --> 00:27:29,410
<i>These chunks
of space debris</i>

446
00:27:29,489 --> 00:27:32,129
<i>are in an elongated orbit
around our sun,</i>

447
00:27:32,209 --> 00:27:33,169
<i>but every now and then</i>

448
00:27:33,250 --> 00:27:34,929
<i>one of them gets bumped</i>

449
00:27:35,009 --> 00:27:37,689
<i>Like a billiard ball
on a pool table</i>

450
00:27:37,769 --> 00:27:39,649
<i>and is knocked
into a different orbit.</i>

451
00:27:39,729 --> 00:27:42,490
If this comet continues
on its path around the sun

452
00:27:42,570 --> 00:27:44,490
and keeps its present course,

453
00:27:44,570 --> 00:27:47,730
sometime on August 1 6,
roughly a year from now,

454
00:27:47,810 --> 00:27:50,010
there's a chance
that we might have impact.

455
00:27:50,090 --> 00:27:54,610
So for the past 8 months,
the United States and Russia

456
00:27:54,689 --> 00:27:58,771
have been building the largest
spaceship ever constructed.

457
00:27:58,850 --> 00:28:01,450
It's being built in orbit
around the Earth.

458
00:28:01,531 --> 00:28:04,170
And we call it the Messiah.

459
00:28:04,371 --> 00:28:08,810
Right now a team of American astronauts and
one Russian are at Cape Canaveral in Florida.

460
00:28:08,810 --> 00:28:12,130
In 2 months, they will leave
on the shuttle Atlantis

461
00:28:12,210 --> 00:28:13,930
to board the Messiah.

462
00:28:14,011 --> 00:28:17,930
This is the crew that will stop the comet.

463
00:28:18,810 --> 00:28:21,410
<i>I'd like the world to meet
some extraordinary people.</i>

464
00:28:21,490 --> 00:28:23,730
<i>First is Mission Commander
Oren Monash.</i>

465
00:28:23,810 --> 00:28:26,490
<i>Commander, would you
introduce us to your team?</i>

466
00:28:26,570 --> 00:28:28,410
I'd be honored, sir.

467
00:28:28,890 --> 00:28:30,369
Pilot Andrea Baker.

468
00:28:30,971 --> 00:28:33,211
Medical Officer Gus Partenza.

469
00:28:33,291 --> 00:28:35,890
From Russia, nuclear specialist

470
00:28:35,970 --> 00:28:38,090
Colonel Mikhail Tulchinsky.

471
00:28:38,170 --> 00:28:39,771
Navigator Mark Simon

472
00:28:39,850 --> 00:28:42,811
and Rendezvous Pilot
Spurgeon Tanner.

473
00:28:42,890 --> 00:28:45,291
Hello,
Mr President.

474
00:28:45,370 --> 00:28:49,051
<i>Captain Tanner,
you flew 6 shuttle missions.</i>

475
00:28:49,132 --> 00:28:51,331
<i>You were the last man to walk
on the moon, weren't you?</i>

476
00:28:51,411 --> 00:28:52,331
Yes, sir, but,

477
00:28:52,811 --> 00:28:54,891
Oren here will be doing
most of the flying on this one.

478
00:28:54,971 --> 00:28:58,050
I'll just be taking us down
to the comet's surface.

479
00:28:58,131 --> 00:28:59,451
Well, it's good to know
we're going to have

480
00:28:59,451 --> 00:29:01,571
<i>your kind of experience up there, Captain.</i>

481
00:29:01,651 --> 00:29:02,371
Tanner: Thank you, sir.

482
00:29:02,450 --> 00:29:03,652
<i>Godspeed to you all.</i>

483
00:29:03,732 --> 00:29:04,771
<i>We're counting on you.</i>

484
00:29:05,372 --> 00:29:06,731
Thank you, sir.

485
00:29:06,731 --> 00:29:09,171
Got Beijing, Rome,
Sao Paulo, Cairo, Berlin!

486
00:29:09,252 --> 00:29:12,132
Does anyone know how big the one
was that killed all the dinosaurs?

487
00:29:12,132 --> 00:29:14,291
Something majestic, mysterious,
with a fanfare for the intro

488
00:29:14,371 --> 00:29:15,692
and a theme for the longer promos.

489
00:29:15,771 --> 00:29:17,451
You want it hitting the goddam Earth?

490
00:29:17,531 --> 00:29:18,811
Well, that's what he's saying.
Bring that up again.

491
00:29:18,892 --> 00:29:20,491
It'll scare the shit out of them.

492
00:29:20,571 --> 00:29:22,452
<i>Beck: We will not tolerate any
disruption four way of life.</i>

493
00:29:22,531 --> 00:29:25,571
Our society will continue as normal.

494
00:29:25,651 --> 00:29:28,851
Work will go on.
You will pay your bills.

495
00:29:28,931 --> 00:29:30,931
[Laughter]

496
00:29:32,251 --> 00:29:34,611
There will be no hoarding.

497
00:29:34,691 --> 00:29:36,892
There will be no sudden profiteering.

498
00:29:36,972 --> 00:29:40,212
I'm freezing all wages, all prices.

499
00:29:40,292 --> 00:29:44,052
What a bottle of water
cost you yesterday...

500
00:29:44,132 --> 00:29:46,611
it will cost you tomorrow.

501
00:29:46,692 --> 00:29:48,011
Now we'll take a few questions.

502
00:29:48,092 --> 00:29:49,452
Reporters: Mr President!

503
00:29:49,531 --> 00:29:50,771
Ms Lerner.

504
00:29:50,852 --> 00:29:52,213
Ahem.

505
00:29:52,292 --> 00:29:55,653
Ahem. Uh, Jenny Lerner, M--MSNBC.

506
00:29:55,732 --> 00:29:57,013
Jenny Lerner?

507
00:29:57,092 --> 00:29:58,452
Son of a bitch.

508
00:29:58,533 --> 00:30:01,292
<i>Um, Mr President,</i>

509
00:30:01,372 --> 00:30:03,412
<i>why wasn't this announcement
made sooner?</i>

510
00:30:03,572 --> 00:30:06,292
Well, until we knew
we could build the rocket

511
00:30:06,372 --> 00:30:10,733
and the comet could be intercepted,
we saw no reason to alarm the planet.

512
00:30:10,813 --> 00:30:12,373
- Sir!
- Mr President!

513
00:30:12,453 --> 00:30:15,012
Do you have another question, Ms Lerner?

514
00:30:15,093 --> 00:30:16,973
Yeah. Um...

515
00:30:17,053 --> 00:30:23,652
<i>Is--Is there a connection between the comet
and the recall of American troops from abroad?</i>

516
00:30:23,652 --> 00:30:25,133
<i>Beck: Our fighting men and women are coming home</i>

517
00:30:25,212 --> 00:30:28,293
<i>because we felt it prudent, in light
of domestic security concerns,</i>

518
00:30:28,372 --> 00:30:29,773
<i>to have them available.</i>

519
00:30:29,852 --> 00:30:31,372
<i>Although I certainly hope
we don't need to use them.</i>

520
00:30:31,453 --> 00:30:32,332
<i>Next question.</i>

521
00:30:32,413 --> 00:30:33,292
