00:59:33,245 --> 00:59:36,966
<i>And while we are confident
the missile attack will succeed,</i>

1017
00:59:37,045 --> 00:59:39,446
<i>it is only prudent that we
now take cautionary steps</i>

1018
00:59:39,525 --> 00:59:42,125
<i>to ensure the continuation
four way of life,</i>

1019
00:59:42,206 --> 00:59:45,285
<i>to guarantee that there
will be enough of us left</i>

1020
00:59:45,366 --> 00:59:47,166
<i>to rebuild a new world</i>

1021
00:59:47,245 --> 00:59:51,006
<i>in the unlikely event that
the comets do strike the Earth.</i>

1022
00:59:51,086 --> 00:59:54,926
So, in the soft limestone of Missouri,

1023
00:59:55,006 --> 00:59:57,766
we've been preparing
a network of immense caves,

1024
00:59:57,846 --> 00:59:59,686
and they're almost finished.

1025
00:59:59,766 --> 01:00:02,326
And we can put
a million people in them.

1026
01:00:02,405 --> 01:00:04,966
And that million people can
survive there, underground,

1027
01:00:05,045 --> 01:00:06,487
for 2 years,

1028
01:00:06,567 --> 01:00:10,406
until the air clears
and the dust settles.

1029
01:00:10,487 --> 01:00:12,846
Now, the cave is more
than a dormitory.

1030
01:00:12,927 --> 01:00:15,007
It's our new Noah's Ark.

1031
01:00:15,086 --> 01:00:17,047
We're storing seeds and seedlings,

1032
01:00:17,126 --> 01:00:20,646
plants, animals,
enough to start over.

1033
01:00:20,726 --> 01:00:22,206
<i>On August 10th, a computer</i>

1034
01:00:22,286 --> 01:00:25,566
<i>will randomly select
800,000 Americans</i>

1035
01:00:25,646 --> 01:00:29,406
<i>to join the 200,000 scientists,
doctors, engineers,</i>

1036
01:00:29,486 --> 01:00:32,526
<i>teachers, soldiers, and artists,
who have already been chosen.</i>

1037
01:00:32,606 --> 01:00:34,526
Other countries
are preparing similar caves

1038
01:00:34,606 --> 01:00:36,406
along whatever lines
they feel are best

1039
01:00:36,486 --> 01:00:38,687
to preserve their way of life.

1040
01:00:38,766 --> 01:00:40,286
This is ours.

1041
01:00:40,367 --> 01:00:44,286
<i>Beginning tonight and continuing
until the crisis passes,</i>

1042
01:00:44,367 --> 01:00:47,487
<i>I am declaring a state
of martial law.</i>

1043
01:00:47,566 --> 01:00:49,246
<i>The armed forces
and the National Guard</i>

1044
01:00:49,326 --> 01:00:52,086
<i>are working
with local law enforcement.</i>

1045
01:00:52,167 --> 01:00:54,648
<i>A national curfew begins
at midnight tonight.</i>

1046
01:00:54,727 --> 01:00:58,247
<i>Now, wherever you are,
go home.</i>

1047
01:00:58,327 --> 01:01:01,087
<i>Stay off the roads
after sunset.</i>

1048
01:01:01,167 --> 01:01:02,727
<i>Crimes against persons
or property</i>

1049
01:01:02,807 --> 01:01:07,167
<i>will be dealt with
swiftly and harshly.</i>

1050
01:01:07,247 --> 01:01:09,567
<i>News stations around the nation
are being faxed copies</i>

1051
01:01:09,647 --> 01:01:11,448
<i>of the lottery procedure as we speak,</i>

1052
01:01:11,527 --> 01:01:15,288
<i>and they'll be broadcasting the
details to you in a few moments.</i>

1053
01:01:22,488 --> 01:01:23,767
I wish...

1054
01:01:26,487 --> 01:01:27,528
No.

1055
01:01:29,407 --> 01:01:31,047
Wishing is wrong.

1056
01:01:31,808 --> 01:01:35,207
It's the wrong word right now.
That's not what I mean.

1057
01:01:36,687 --> 01:01:38,367
What I mean is...

1058
01:01:40,167 --> 01:01:42,328
I believe in God.

1059
01:01:42,408 --> 01:01:44,568
Relax.

1060
01:01:44,648 --> 01:01:47,207
<i>I know a lot of you don't,</i>

1061
01:01:47,288 --> 01:01:49,048
<i>but I still want
to offer a prayer...</i>

1062
01:01:50,207 --> 01:01:51,808
<i>for our survival.</i>

1063
01:01:53,247 --> 01:01:54,487
<i>Mine included.</i>

1064
01:01:55,688 --> 01:01:58,649
<i>Because I believe that God,</i>

1065
01:01:58,728 --> 01:02:00,449
<i>whomever you hold that to be,</i>

1066
01:02:00,528 --> 01:02:03,448
hears all prayers,

1067
01:02:03,528 --> 01:02:06,288
even if sometimes the answer is no.

1068
01:02:07,489 --> 01:02:10,288
So, may the Lord bless you.

1069
01:02:10,369 --> 01:02:12,768
May the Lord keep you.

1070
01:02:12,848 --> 01:02:16,009
May the Lord lift up His divine
countenance upon you...

1071
01:02:17,809 --> 01:02:19,969
and give you peace.

1072
01:02:24,329 --> 01:02:28,768
<i>Woman:
And in 5, 4, 3, 2...</i>

1073
01:02:37,008 --> 01:02:40,168
<i>We now have the details
for the national lottery.</i>

1074
01:02:42,008 --> 01:02:43,768
<i>"Those of you
who have been preselected</i>

1075
01:02:43,848 --> 01:02:47,369
<i>will be notified
within the next few minutes.</i>

1076
01:02:47,449 --> 01:02:50,049
<i>For the rest, on the night
of August 1 0th,</i>

1077
01:02:50,129 --> 01:02:52,129
<i>those whose social
security numbers</i>

1078
01:02:52,209 --> 01:02:56,048
<i>have been randomly selected
by computer will be notified.</i>

1079
01:02:56,129 --> 01:02:59,809
<i>While some Americans...
over 50 years of age</i>

1080
01:02:59,888 --> 01:03:02,049
<i>have been preselected
for the ARK</i>

1081
01:03:02,129 --> 01:03:05,490
<i>due to their expertise
in a necessary field of study,</i>

1082
01:03:05,570 --> 01:03:09,170
<i>no men and women over 50
in the general population</i>

1083
01:03:09,249 --> 01:03:11,490
<i>will be included
in the lottery.</i>

1084
01:03:18,970 --> 01:03:20,010
The...

1085
01:03:20,770 --> 01:03:22,890
<i>The evac--The evacuation
of those</i>

1086
01:03:22,970 --> 01:03:24,690
<i>who have been selected
for the ARK</i>

1087
01:03:24,770 --> 01:03:26,370
<i>will take no longer
than 2 days,</i>

1088
01:03:26,450 --> 01:03:27,890
<i>beginning on August 12th.</i>

1089
01:03:27,970 --> 01:03:30,250
<i>During this 2-day period,</i>

1090
01:03:30,330 --> 01:03:32,690
<i>no unofficial travel
will be permitted.</i>

1091
01:03:32,770 --> 01:03:35,130
<i>Those selected will be
taken by bus and train</i>

1092
01:03:35,210 --> 01:03:38,849
<i>to the underground ARK site
by military personnel.</i>

1093
01:03:38,930 --> 01:03:42,370
<i>Civil defence teams
have been formed in every town</i>

1094
01:03:42,449 --> 01:03:45,049
<i>with a population over 5,000.</i>

1095
01:03:45,130 --> 01:03:48,130
<i>They will distribute supplies
and organize group shelters</i>

1096
01:03:48,209 --> 01:03:49,889
<i>in underground
parking facilities</i>

1097
01:03:49,969 --> 01:03:51,890
<i>and other
appropriate sites.</i>

1098
01:03:51,971 --> 01:03:53,170
<i>Construction plans..."</i>

1099
01:03:53,250 --> 01:03:54,250
[Telephone Rings]

1100
01:03:54,331 --> 01:03:55,810
<i>"Equipment lists,</i>

1101
01:03:55,890 --> 01:03:58,090
<i>and locations for securing
the necessary provisions..."</i>

1102
01:03:58,171 --> 01:03:59,850
Ellen: Hello?

1103
01:03:59,930 --> 01:04:01,330
Yes, this is
Ellen Biederman.

1104
01:04:01,410 --> 01:04:03,010
<i>Jenny: "...on how to grow
your own food underground</i>

1105
01:04:03,090 --> 01:04:05,210
<i>and how to purify water</i>

1106
01:04:05,290 --> 01:04:07,650
<i>are now available on
the internet at www..."</i>

1107
01:04:07,731 --> 01:04:09,731
We've been preselected.

1108
01:04:09,811 --> 01:04:14,370
<i>Jenny: "...fcda.gov."</i>

1109
01:04:14,451 --> 01:04:16,971
Chuck? Chuck?
Where are you going?

1110
01:04:17,051 --> 01:04:18,370
Our phone.
They could be calling.

1111
01:04:18,451 --> 01:04:20,091
<i>Jenny:
"...beginning on August 9th.</i>

1112
01:04:20,170 --> 01:04:22,931
<i>The only phones that ring</i>

1113
01:04:23,011 --> 01:04:25,411
<i>will be those of the people selected."</i>

1114
01:04:26,731 --> 01:04:28,771
That's it.

1115
01:04:28,851 --> 01:04:30,171
That's all there is.

1116
01:04:38,251 --> 01:04:41,251
<i>Tanner: The interior
camera circuitry is shot.</i>

1117
01:04:41,331 --> 01:04:42,931
<i>So, Andy, can we get back
into the cargo bay</i>

1118
01:04:43,011 --> 01:04:44,771
<i>to reroute the video functions?</i>

1119
01:04:44,851 --> 01:04:46,691
<i>Baker: Starboard cargo porthole's blown.</i>

1120
01:04:46,771 --> 01:04:50,211
We could go in with the EVAs, but there's
not  much left in the life-support packs.

1121
01:04:50,211 --> 01:04:51,970
Simon: We should be able
to raise Houston

1122
01:04:52,051 --> 01:04:53,691
on the low band once we get closer.

1123
01:04:53,770 --> 01:04:55,811
And the Orion is still functioning?

1124
01:04:55,892 --> 01:04:57,252
System check was OK,

1125
01:04:57,331 --> 01:04:59,852
but I don't know about
the radiation shielding.

1126
01:04:59,931 --> 01:05:03,732
So, if we fire it up, we beat
the comet back to Earth, but

1127
01:05:03,732 --> 01:05:06,971
we may end up glowing
in the dark. Right?

1128
01:05:09,092 --> 01:05:11,852
Tanner, Laughing:
OK, so, uh...

1129
01:05:13,252 --> 01:05:14,532
Anybody?

1130
01:05:23,091 --> 01:05:24,732
Let's go home.

1131
01:05:30,733 --> 01:05:31,612
OK.

1132
01:05:41,532 --> 01:05:42,813
Robin: I have to say it's liberating

1133
01:05:42,892 --> 01:05:45,492
knowing that I'm not
going to be called.

1134
01:05:45,573 --> 01:05:47,852
I don't think I've ever been happier.

1135
01:05:47,932 --> 01:05:50,412
I've even stopped smoking.

1136
01:05:50,492 --> 01:05:54,252
What are you gonna do with
all that extra money you save?

1137
01:05:56,252 --> 01:05:58,853
Do you know the National Gallery
is saving all of the art?

1138
01:05:58,892 --> 01:06:01,013
They're shipping it to the caves.

1139
01:06:01,092 --> 01:06:03,852
I've given them my beautiful
18th-century desk

1140
01:06:03,933 --> 01:06:06,892
from New England and
all the Sheraton silver.

1141
01:06:06,973 --> 01:06:12,812
I really feel like I'd protected
something when I gave them.

1142
01:06:14,172 --> 01:06:15,894
You should see my apartment.

1143
01:06:15,973 --> 01:06:17,213
There's nothing there.

1144
01:06:17,293 --> 01:06:19,454
It's practically Japanese.

1145
01:06:22,413 --> 01:06:24,813
Seems kind of unfair
that I got picked.

1146
01:06:24,893 --> 01:06:27,692
You know, I'm not
a doctor or a scientist.

1147
01:06:29,333 --> 01:06:31,094
People need continuity.

1148
01:06:31,174 --> 01:06:33,174
Everyone knows you.

1149
01:06:33,254 --> 01:06:35,694
And they trust you.

1150
01:06:35,774 --> 01:06:39,373
But l...can't help you.

1151
01:06:39,454 --> 01:06:41,334
Don't worry about me.

1152
01:06:41,413 --> 01:06:42,614
I'm gonna be happy

1153
01:06:42,693 --> 01:06:45,813
as long as I know
you're going to live.

1154
01:06:53,413 --> 01:06:55,254
[Sirens]

1155
01:07:04,294 --> 01:07:05,094
Mr Hotchner?

1156
01:07:05,174 --> 01:07:08,173
Who did I think I was gonna be
when I bought that bike?

1157
01:07:08,254 --> 01:07:11,053
Well, every kid on
the block wants one now.

1158
01:07:11,134 --> 01:07:13,174
Every parent on the block
hates you for it.

1159
01:07:13,253 --> 01:07:15,293
Thank you Leo, that's the
best news I've had in years.

1160
01:07:15,374 --> 01:07:16,494
Um, sir?

1161
01:07:16,573 --> 01:07:18,134
Could you give me a hand
over here for a second?

1162
01:07:18,213 --> 01:07:19,053
Yes, sir.

1163
01:07:19,134 --> 01:07:20,575
I just want to get
these bars up.

1164
01:07:20,654 --> 01:07:21,774
Hi, Mrs Hotchner.

1165
01:07:21,855 --> 01:07:23,215
<i>Jenny On TV: A mob
attacked and killed</i>

1166
01:07:23,294 --> 01:07:25,135
<i>a Miami rental yard operator</i>

1167
01:07:25,214 --> 01:07:29,535
<i>who was charging $5,000 an hour
for backhoe and tractor rentals.</i>

1168
01:07:29,614 --> 01:07:33,174
<i>Marines intervened to stop the violence.
Arizona...</i>

1169
01:07:33,255 --> 01:07:34,134
Mrs Hotchner?

1170
01:07:34,215 --> 01:07:35,255
Sarah's on the hill.

1171
01:07:35,335 --> 01:07:36,695
Thank you.

1172
01:07:36,775 --> 01:07:38,375
[Helicopters]

1173
01:07:43,655 --> 01:07:45,095
Where were you today?

1174
01:07:46,335 --> 01:07:48,415
I've been looking all over for you.

1175
01:07:48,494 --> 01:07:50,215
Why weren't you at school?

1176
01:07:50,294 --> 01:07:52,214
My dad said I didn't have to go.

1177
01:07:52,295 --> 01:07:54,414
He said there's no point.

1178
01:08:00,375 --> 01:08:01,615
I talked to Civil Defence.  They said

1179
01:08:01,654 --> 01:08:06,054
if you and I got married
we'd be family, and I could get you in

1180
01:08:06,175 --> 01:08:09,295
What about my parents?
They're not your family.

1181
01:08:09,375 --> 01:08:10,895
I don't want to go
without my parents.

1182
01:08:10,976 --> 01:08:13,455
You don't have to. I'm
the famous Leo Biederman,

1183
01:08:13,535 --> 01:08:15,935
and I haven't used
my fame for anything,

1184
01:08:16,015 --> 01:08:17,615
but I got them to let
your family go, too.

1185
01:08:23,335 --> 01:08:26,416
You--This is your
only chance to survive.

1186
01:08:41,736 --> 01:08:43,376
<i>Jenny: Across the country,</i>

1187
01:08:43,456 --> 01:08:46,576
<i>Looters continue to set fire
to abandoned stores.</i>

1188
01:08:46,656 --> 01:08:49,456
<i>The fires have been left to burn
since many fire fighters</i>

1189
01:08:49,536 --> 01:08:51,776
<i>have been called
to help prepare shelters.</i>

1190
01:08:51,855 --> 01:08:54,576
<i>Throughout Latin America's
major cities,</i>

1191
01:08:54,656 --> 01:08:57,416
<i>business districts have been
abandoned to looting gangs...</i>

1192
01:09:05,055 --> 01:09:09,135
<i>Airlifts have been ruled out
as too dangerous.</i>

1193
01:09:09,216 --> 01:09:11,255
<i>More street fighting in Moscow</i>

1194
01:09:11,335 --> 01:09:13,176
<i>as food and fuel shortages continue.</i>

1195
01:09:25,096 --> 01:09:28,777
<i>Priest:
Believes all things, hopes all things,</i>

1196
01:09:28,857 --> 01:09:31,697
<i>endures all things.</i>

1197
01:09:31,776 --> 01:09:34,857
<i>When I was a child,
I spoke like a child,</i>

1198
01:09:34,936 --> 01:09:39,017
<i>I thought like a child, I reasoned like a child.</i>

1199
01:09:39,097 --> 01:09:43,576
<i>When I became a man,
I gave up childish ways.</i>

1200
01:09:43,658 --> 01:09:46,018
<i>For now we see in a mirror dimly,</i>

1201
01:09:46,097 --> 01:09:48,417
<i>but then face to face.</i>

1202
01:09:48,498 --> 01:09:50,138
<i>Now I know in part,</i>

1203
01:09:50,217 --> 01:09:52,777
<i>then I shall understand fully,</i>

1204
01:09:52,857 --> 01:09:55,577
<i>even as I have been
fully understood.</i>

1205
01:10:05,097 --> 01:10:09,257
<i>Do you, Leo, take Sarah
to be your wife...</i>

1206
01:10:09,337 --> 01:10:12,536
to have and to hold
from this day forward...

1207
01:10:12,617 --> 01:10:14,657
<i>for better, for worse...</i>

1208
01:10:14,736 --> 01:10:17,018
<i>for richer, for poorer...</i>

1209
01:10:17,098 --> 01:10:19,058
<i>to love and to cherish?</i>

1210
01:10:27,057 --> 01:10:29,897
<i>I now pronounce you
husband and wife.</i>

1211
01:10:40,298 --> 01:10:42,178
[Clock Ticking]

1212
01:11:18,538 --> 01:11:20,619
[Console Beeps]

1213
01:11:20,698 --> 01:11:22,699
[Morash Groans]

1214
01:11:45,739 --> 01:11:47,979
Here, let me help you.

1215
01:11:48,059 --> 01:11:49,059
I'll get it.

1216
01:11:51,179 --> 01:11:54,860
Yeah.  How you feeling?

1217
01:11:54,940 --> 01:11:56,300
All right.

1218
01:11:56,380 --> 01:11:57,980
I want to tell you something.

1219
01:11:58,060 --> 01:11:59,779
You children didn't bring
any real books to read,

1220
01:11:59,900 --> 01:12:01,260
did you know that?

1221
01:12:01,340 --> 01:12:03,740
I brought Moby Dick
and Huckleberry Finn

1222
01:12:03,820 --> 01:12:06,819
and Baker and Simon
had never read them.

1223
01:12:06,939 --> 01:12:09,220
Now, I'm afraid to ask you,

1224
01:12:09,340 --> 01:12:12,299
have you ever read Melville or Twain?

1225
01:12:12,380 --> 01:12:13,620
Hmm?

1226
01:12:13,740 --> 01:12:17,419
Hey, I'm a child of the movies, Fish.

1227
01:12:17,499 --> 01:12:20,139
OK, I see.

1228
01:12:20,219 --> 01:12:22,539
So...

1229
01:12:22,619 --> 01:12:25,260
You got a shitty deal,
Oren, you know that?

1230
01:12:25,340 --> 01:12:26,860
You really did.

1231
01:12:26,940 --> 01:12:28,260
Don't worry about me.

1232
01:12:28,380 --> 01:12:29,500
Yeah.

1233
01:12:29,580 --> 01:12:31,860
I mean that. Really.

1234
01:12:31,980 --> 01:12:33,819
Don't worry about me.

1235
01:12:33,900 --> 01:12:37,020
My whole life l...

1236
01:12:40,301 --> 01:12:42,381
You know how it is for guys like us.

1237
01:12:43,661 --> 01:12:46,860
You--You and l, we're the same.

1238
01:12:46,941 --> 01:12:49,180
What do you mean
by that?

1239
01:12:49,261 --> 01:12:50,620
Gotta be the best.

1240
01:12:50,700 --> 01:12:52,780
Oh, I see.

1241
01:12:52,860 --> 01:12:56,141
Be...the best.

1242
01:12:56,220 --> 01:12:58,061
[Sighs]

1243
01:13:07,420 --> 01:13:09,180
Sometimes I see...

1244
01:13:09,301 --> 01:13:11,301
flashes of light...

1245
01:13:11,421 --> 01:13:15,500
You know, like...colors.

1246
01:13:17,020 --> 01:13:19,181
I fall asleep...

1247
01:13:19,260 --> 01:13:22,021
and I dream.

1248
01:13:22,140 --> 01:13:25,020
But there's a part of me
that's always awake.

1249
01:13:25,100 --> 01:13:28,221
And I can see myself dreaming.

1250
01:13:32,701 --> 01:13:35,821
I'm seeing things differently, Fish.

1251
01:13:35,901 --> 01:13:38,381
Well, that's good.

1252
01:13:38,461 --> 01:13:42,021
Fish...

1253
01:13:42,141 --> 01:13:44,261
why the hell do they call you "Fish"?

1254
01:13:44,381 --> 01:13:47,181
[Laughs]
Well, l...

1255
01:13:47,262 --> 01:13:49,781
Spurgeon, sturgeon, fish.

1256
01:13:49,982 --> 01:13:53,101
They took about 15 minutes of my
first day at the Naval Academy.

1257
01:13:53,142 --> 01:13:55,342
Yeah.

1258
01:13:55,421 --> 01:13:57,862
Your kids go there?

1259
01:13:57,982 --> 01:14:00,541
Yeah, they did.
They did.

1260
01:14:00,622 --> 01:14:02,862
And they're good men, both of them.

1261
01:14:02,943 --> 01:14:06,742
I don't see as much of them as
I used to when Mary was alive.

1262
01:14:07,022 --> 01:14:08,822
You don't have to talk
about it. It's OK.

1263
01:14:08,942 --> 01:14:11,342
No, it's OK. It's OK.

1264
01:14:11,422 --> 01:14:13,422
You're a married man.
You know what it's like.

1265
01:14:13,502 --> 01:14:17,022
Every marriage has its
good years and bad years.

1266
01:14:17,102 --> 01:14:19,022
We ended on a great year.

1267
01:14:23,022 --> 01:14:25,422
Yeah.

1268
01:14:25,502 --> 01:14:26,942
Anyway, let's get started.

1269
01:14:29,021 --> 01:14:30,661
Moby Dick.  Chapter one.

1270
01:14:30,782 --> 01:14:33,582
[Laughing]

1271
01:14:34,582 --> 01:14:35,822
"Call me Ishmael.

1272
01:14:35,822 --> 01:14:38,942
Several years ago, never
mind how long precisely,

1273
01:14:39,022 --> 01:14:41,422
having little or
no money in my purse...

1274
01:14:41,502 --> 01:14:43,502
grim about the mouth...

1275
01:14:43,582 --> 01:14:47,102
Whenever it is a damp,
drizzly November in my soul,

1276
01:14:47,182 --> 01:14:49,263
whenever I find myself...

1277
01:14:49,343 --> 01:14:51,543
...knocking people's hats off, then,

1278
01:14:51,663 --> 01:14:53,543
I account it high time

1279
01:14:53,663 --> 01:14:56,823
to get to sea as soon as I can."

1280
01:15:11,504 --> 01:15:11,743
Listen up!

1281
01:15:11,823 --> 01:15:13,304
<i>Hold it right there!</i>

1282
01:15:13,424 --> 01:15:14,303
- Biederman?
- That's us.

1283
01:15:14,384 --> 01:15:15,423
IDs, please.

1284
01:15:15,504 --> 01:15:16,663
Yeah. Got them right here.

1285
01:15:16,783 --> 01:15:17,663
There's 4 of us.

1286
01:15:17,743 --> 01:15:20,063
Lieutenant: Lewis?

1287
01:15:20,143 --> 01:15:22,063
This is my wife Sarah.
We have a marriage license.

1288
01:15:22,143 --> 01:15:24,263
Um, I have it right here.

1289
01:15:30,303 --> 01:15:31,463
OK.

1290
01:15:32,463 --> 01:15:34,543
All right. Let's go.
Let's move it out!

1291
01:15:34,623 --> 01:15:37,623
Mom? Sir? My parents
are coming, too.

1292
01:15:37,743 --> 01:15:39,224
Wait! The Hotchners.

1293
01:15:39,344 --> 01:15:40,663
H-O-T-C--

1294
01:15:40,783 --> 01:15:42,663
H-N-E-R.

1295
01:15:43,184 --> 01:15:44,183
It's not here.

1296
01:15:44,304 --> 01:15:45,583
No no.  It has to be there.

1297
01:15:45,664 --> 01:15:47,263
FCDA sent their names
to the White House.

1298
01:15:47,263 --> 01:15:49,823
- They're not there.
- Just check the goddam list again.

1299
01:15:49,983 --> 01:15:51,623
- Give me your bag
- They must be there.

1300
01:15:51,663 --> 01:15:52,944
Dan: Give me your bag, sweetie.

1301
01:15:53,024 --> 01:15:54,624
- No, they're not on the list.  I'm sorry.
- Wait, wait...

1302
01:15:55,104 --> 01:15:56,384
Let's go!

1303
01:15:56,464 --> 01:15:58,624
Sir! Could you check
it one more time?

1304
01:15:58,704 --> 01:16:01,664
I put you on the list.
They said you're on the list.

1305
01:16:01,744 --> 01:16:05,264
- Sarah, I put them on the list!
- We're not on the list.

1306
01:16:05,504 --> 01:16:07,544
Lieutenant:
I need the Biedermans on the bus now.

1307
01:16:07,664 --> 01:16:09,385
- What?
- I want to stay with you.

1308
01:16:09,505 --> 01:16:12,225
No, no, no, no!

1309
01:16:12,304 --> 01:16:13,664
I need to stay with you!

1310
01:16:13,745 --> 01:16:17,745
- Sarah! Sarah, you need to go.
- No. I have to stay with you, dad

1311
01:16:17,824 --> 01:16:19,584
I'm not going anywhere without you!

1312
01:16:19,665 --> 01:16:21,384
- Honey, get on the bus!
- Sarah, you don't know what you're doing

1313
01:16:21,504 --> 01:16:23,105
Young lady, this bus is moving out.

1314
01:16:23,505 --> 01:16:26,384
Dan: Son, on the bus!  Get on the bus!

1315
01:16:27,344 --> 01:16:29,744
Chuck, we'll work it out
when we get there.

1316
01:16:38,784 --> 01:16:40,584
[Sobbing]

1317
01:16:49,904 --> 01:16:52,585
Jenny? There's a phone call for you.

1318
01:16:56,145 --> 01:16:57,585
Yes?

1319
01:16:57,666 --> 01:16:59,665
This is she.

1320
01:16:59,746 --> 01:17:01,745
Is Robin Lerner my mother?

1321
01:17:09,665 --> 01:17:10,545
When?

1322
01:17:15,426 --> 01:17:16,866
Uh, 61 .

1323
01:17:19,266 --> 01:17:22,825
I'll come down there then.
Thank you.

1324
01:17:22,945 --> 01:17:24,506
Thank you very much.

1325
01:17:28,305 --> 01:17:30,385
Jenny, do you want us
to do something?

1326
01:18:31,907 --> 01:18:35,587
You're too late. I already
took care of everything.

1327
01:18:37,826 --> 01:18:41,107
Come. Inside the car.
You're getting sick. Please.

1328
01:18:41,186 --> 01:18:42,786
I want to talk to you.

1329
01:18:44,706 --> 01:18:46,226
Please, come.

1330
01:18:48,146 --> 01:18:49,707
I don't give a shit.

1331
01:18:49,827 --> 01:18:51,467
Go home and tell it to Chloe.

1332
01:18:51,587 --> 01:18:53,227
I can't.  She left me.

1333
01:18:53,267 --> 01:18:56,147
She's with her mother.
They both got scared.

1334
01:18:56,307 --> 01:18:58,507
Come. I want to talk to you.

1335
01:18:58,627 --> 01:19:00,467
I need you.

1336
01:19:00,866 --> 01:19:02,347
How does it feel?

1337
01:19:06,468 --> 01:19:08,468
I feel like an orphan.

1338
01:19:11,268 --> 01:19:13,428
Jenny!  Jenny!

1339
01:19:16,787 --> 01:19:18,108
Stop.

1340
01:19:46,147 --> 01:19:47,947
[People Shouting]

1341
01:20:20,469 --> 01:20:21,989
[Crying]

1342
01:20:29,190 --> 01:20:32,470
Welcome to the ARK. I'm
section leader for Orange 254.

1343
01:20:32,549 --> 01:20:35,109
Remember that.  That's where you'll
be calling home the next 2 years.

1344
01:20:35,189 --> 01:20:38,229
So gather your things and follow
me to the orientation gallery.

1345
01:20:38,790 --> 01:20:40,589
[Helicopters]

1346
01:20:40,709 --> 01:20:44,669
<i>P.A.: If you have been designated
as a civilian section officer,</i>

1347
01:20:44,709 --> 01:20:49,469
<i>report to section Red 116 upon entering.</i>

1348
01:20:49,589 --> 01:20:54,028
<i>Once again, if you have been
designated as a civilian section officer,</i>

1349
01:20:54,149 --> 01:20:58,309
<i>report to section Red 116 upon entering.</i>

1350
01:20:59,750 --> 01:21:02,390
Dan: Leo...

1351
01:21:02,470 --> 01:21:03,990
I'm not coming.

1352
01:21:04,069 --> 01:21:07,469
Leo, come with us right now.

1353
01:21:07,590 --> 01:21:09,110
I have to go back for Sarah.

1354
01:21:09,189 --> 01:21:10,070
Leo--

1355
01:21:10,149 --> 01:21:12,069
Mom, I'm going.

1356
01:21:17,990 --> 01:21:18,950
Don, what are you doing?

1357
01:21:19,030 --> 01:21:21,310
Giving him something to trade,
that's what I'm doing.

1358
01:21:21,590 --> 01:21:23,030
I want you to take this.

1359
01:21:23,109 --> 01:21:24,390
Dad, that's enough.

1360
01:21:29,910 --> 01:21:31,671
[Crying]
Goddam it.

1361
01:21:31,750 --> 01:21:33,351
You take care of yourself, OK?

1362
01:21:37,110 --> 01:21:38,230
I'm gonna make it.

1363
01:21:48,630 --> 01:21:50,111
Worth:
What about Entrekin?

1364
01:21:50,230 --> 01:21:52,790
I don't know. He hasn't
returned my call in 2 weeks.

1365
01:21:52,870 --> 01:21:54,190
- Excuse me, Jenny?
- Yeah?

1366
01:21:54,310 --> 01:21:55,870
Your father's here.

1367
01:22:01,109 --> 01:22:02,230
Hello.

1368
01:22:02,311 --> 01:22:03,951
Hello.

1369
01:22:04,071 --> 01:22:05,790
I can't stay long.
I'm leaving the city,

1370
01:22:05,910 --> 01:22:08,471
but I wanted to show you something.

1371
01:22:08,550 --> 01:22:10,951
I wanted to show you that
you're not an orphan.

1372
01:22:14,951 --> 01:22:17,590
I have proof that
you're not an orphan.

1373
01:22:17,671 --> 01:22:19,472
Here.

1374
01:22:22,391 --> 01:22:23,351
Look.

1375
01:22:32,551 --> 01:22:34,792
Where's Mom?

1376
01:22:34,872 --> 01:22:36,312
Behind the camera.

1377
01:22:37,832 --> 01:22:39,152
She took this?

1378
01:22:39,272 --> 01:22:40,152
Mm-hmm.

1379
01:22:40,232 --> 01:22:43,192
And this one, too.

1380
01:22:43,272 --> 01:22:45,551
She was such an artist,
don't you think so?

1381
01:22:47,672 --> 01:22:49,512
You don't remember
when we take them, hmm?

1382
01:22:49,592 --> 01:22:52,591
I'm 5 years old. How
would I remember that?

1383
01:22:52,711 --> 01:22:56,871
Some people do remember
when they were 5 years old.

1384
01:22:59,351 --> 01:23:01,551
It was such a beautiful day.

1385
01:23:01,671 --> 01:23:03,831
All alone on the beach.

1386
01:23:05,511 --> 01:23:08,512
And, of course, she would
have been in the picture,

1387
01:23:08,632 --> 01:23:12,752
but there was no one else
to hold the camera,

1388
01:23:12,872 --> 01:23:15,992
and...she insisted.

1389
01:23:16,072 --> 01:23:18,552
You know how she is.

1390
01:23:18,631 --> 01:23:20,312
How she was.

1391
01:23:22,071 --> 01:23:23,913
Jenny.

1392
01:23:27,992 --> 01:23:30,272
It was such a good day

1393
01:23:30,393 --> 01:23:32,792
for all of us.

1394
01:23:32,872 --> 01:23:34,633
Don't you remember?

1395
01:23:40,873 --> 01:23:42,313
Keep them.

1396
01:23:45,753 --> 01:23:47,272
Goodbye.

1397
01:24:02,952 --> 01:24:04,072
[Sniffles]

1398
01:24:19,113 --> 01:24:21,753
<i>Radio: We have now confirmed the
launch of all the Titan missiles</i>

1399
01:24:21,753 --> 01:24:25,033
<i>from their positions in
North Dakota and Wyoming.</i>

1400
01:24:25,113 --> 01:24:30,314
<i>The comets are now approximately 14 hours
outside of Earth's atmosphere,</i>

1401
01:24:30,353 --> 01:24:32,153
<i>and we are told it should
take these missiles</i>

1402
01:24:32,153 --> 01:24:35,433
<i>Less than 20 minutes
to reach their target.</i>

1403
01:24:35,713 --> 01:24:37,594
Jenny: OK, here's what we're looking at.

1404
01:24:37,673 --> 01:24:40,034
All of the Titans have been launched.

1405
01:24:40,074 --> 01:24:43,114
We still won't know if
they've made a difference.

1406
01:24:43,195 --> 01:24:45,514
The comets have to travel for a while

1407
01:24:45,594 --> 01:24:47,914
before the radar tracking
stations can see

1408
01:24:47,994 --> 01:24:51,634
if they've been pushed to a safe
course that'll bypass the Earth.

1409
01:24:51,674 --> 01:24:55,434
So, one more time
we have to wait.

1410
01:25:14,113 --> 01:25:15,155
Are we on?

1411
01:25:15,234 --> 01:25:17,034
Cameraman: We're on, Mr President.

1412
01:25:26,634 --> 01:25:28,234
Our missiles have failed.

1413
01:25:29,994 --> 01:25:35,354
The comets are still headed for Earth...

1414
01:25:35,435 --> 01:25:37,554
and there's nothing
we can do to stop them.

1415
01:25:40,475 --> 01:25:43,395
So, this is it.

1416
01:25:43,515 --> 01:25:46,155
If the world does go on...

1417
01:25:46,234 --> 01:25:48,715
it will not go on for everyone.

1418
01:25:49,596 --> 01:25:53,755
<i>We have now been able to calculate
the comets' final trajectories,</i>

1419
01:25:53,755 --> 01:25:56,996
<i>and we have determined where
they're going to strike.</i>

1420
01:25:57,195 --> 01:26:00,555
The smaller of the 2 comets,
Biederman, will hit first,

1421
01:26:00,635 --> 01:26:02,435
somewhere along
the Atlantic Seaboard

1422
01:26:02,555 --> 01:26:05,275
probably in the waters off
the coast of Cape Hatteras

1423
01:26:05,355 --> 01:26:09,035
in just under 12 hours at
4:35 p.m. eastern daylight time.

1424
01:26:09,115 --> 01:26:13,195
The impact of the comet
is going to be...

1425
01:26:13,275 --> 01:26:15,595
Well, disastrous.

1426
01:26:15,915 --> 01:26:20,395
<i>There will be a very large tidal wave
moving quickly through the Atlantic Ocean</i>

1427
01:26:20,395 --> 01:26:22,236
<i>It will be 100 feet high,</i>

1428
01:26:22,315 --> 01:26:27,075
traveling at 1,100 miles an hour.
That's faster than the speed of sound.

1429
01:26:27,075 --> 01:26:29,475
As the wave reaches shallow water,
it's going to slow down,

1430
01:26:29,595 --> 01:26:30,915
but the wave height,

1431
01:26:31,036 --> 01:26:33,275
depending on the depth
of the shelf off the coast,

1432
01:26:33,356 --> 01:26:37,676
<i>will be anywhere from
1 ,000 to 3,500 feet high.</i>

1433
01:26:39,596 --> 01:26:45,796
<i>Where the land is flat, the wave
will wash inland 600 to 700 miles</i>

1434
01:26:45,836 --> 01:26:50,756
<i>The wave will hit our nation's
capital 40 minutes after impact.</i>

1435
01:26:50,955 --> 01:26:57,077
<i>New York City, Boston,
Atlanta, Philadelphia...</i>

1436
01:26:57,156 --> 01:26:58,957
<i>all will be destroyed.</i>

1437
01:26:59,196 --> 01:27:02,396
<i>If you have any means of getting
away from the path of this wave,</i>

1438
01:27:02,876 --> 01:27:04,757
<i>Leave now.</i>

1439
01:27:04,877 --> 01:27:07,436
<i>The impact of the larger comet</i>

1440
01:27:07,517 --> 01:27:10,516
<i>will be nothing less than
an extinction-level event.</i>

1441
01:27:10,636 --> 01:27:13,356
<i>It will strike land
in Western Canada</i>

1442
01:27:13,436 --> 01:27:15,436
<i>3 hours after Biederman.</i>

1443
01:27:16,156 --> 01:27:19,156
Within a week, the skies will be
dark with dust from the impact

1444
01:27:19,196 --> 01:27:22,316
and they will stay dark for 2 years.

1445
01:27:22,396 --> 01:27:26,397
All plant life will be dead within...

1446
01:27:26,476 --> 01:27:29,037
4 weeks.

1447
01:27:29,117 --> 01:27:32,396
Animal life within...

1448
01:27:32,477 --> 01:27:34,156
a few months.

1449
01:27:37,036 --> 01:27:39,317
So that's it.

1450
01:27:39,598 --> 01:27:41,398
Good luck to us all.

1451
01:28:06,878 --> 01:28:09,277
Fish: Could I bother
everyone for a minute?

1452
01:28:09,358 --> 01:28:11,197
Let's take a look at the big one.

1453
01:28:11,278 --> 01:28:13,998
Now, the outgassing has created a vent

1454
01:28:14,077 --> 01:28:16,478
a half mile wide and
at least 2 miles deep.

1455
01:28:16,557 --> 01:28:18,317
Comet gets closer to the sun,
sun melts the ice,

1456
01:28:18,397 --> 01:28:22,157
ice turns to steam,
we get a big hole, OK?

1457
01:28:22,317 --> 01:28:26,157
So, how many nukes do we
have left in the back?

1458
01:28:26,237 --> 01:28:28,398
4.

1459
01:28:28,478 --> 01:28:32,918
If we can get the remaining
bombs in that vent,

1460
01:28:33,038 --> 01:28:36,837
there shouldn't be anything
left bigger than a suitcase.

1461
01:28:36,958 --> 01:28:38,598
We can't do anything about the little one,

1462
01:28:38,718 --> 01:28:42,638
but it just might give them a chance.

1463
01:28:42,718 --> 01:28:44,558
Without the arming codes,

1464
01:28:44,639 --> 01:28:47,079
we're going to have to wait
to set the bomb timers

1465
01:28:47,199 --> 01:28:49,279
until we get closer to Earth
to raise Houston.

1466
01:28:49,358 --> 01:28:52,159
We may not have enough
life support left

1467
01:28:52,238 --> 01:28:54,158
to get back into the
cargo bay for the nukes,

1468
01:28:54,239 --> 01:28:56,238
much less to go down to the comet.

1469
01:28:56,318 --> 01:28:57,998
We sure as hell don't have
enough propellant left

1470
01:28:58,079 --> 01:29:01,359
in the Messiah to maneuver with.

1471
01:29:01,439 --> 01:29:04,359
How are we supposed to get
back off the surface

1472
01:29:04,479 --> 01:29:06,399
once we've gotten down there?

1473
01:29:11,159 --> 01:29:12,758
We don't.

1474
01:29:21,119 --> 01:29:23,918
Well, look at the bright side.

1475
01:29:23,999 --> 01:29:26,839
We'll all have
high schools named after us.

1476
01:29:45,439 --> 01:29:47,359
[Static Crackling]

1477
01:29:47,439 --> 01:29:50,120
<i>Tanner: Houston, this is Messiah.</i>

1478
01:29:50,239 --> 01:29:53,359
<i>Houston, this is Messiah.</i>

1479
01:30:04,960 --> 01:30:07,040
Nice of you to call, Messiah.

1480
01:30:07,040 --> 01:30:09,401
We were beginning to wonder
what you were doing up there.

1481
01:30:09,440 --> 01:30:10,680
<i>Tanner: Admiring the view, Houston.</i>

1482
01:30:10,800 --> 01:30:12,200
Fish, is that you?

1483
01:30:12,320 --> 01:30:14,760
Yep. We don't have time
to talk, Houston.

1484
01:30:14,840 --> 01:30:16,240
There's nothing we can do
about the smaller one,

1485
01:30:16,240 --> 01:30:17,880
<i>but we do have a plan.</i>

1486
01:30:18,000 --> 01:30:20,400
<i>We need the arming codes
for the last 4 nukes.</i>

1487
01:30:20,480 --> 01:30:21,840
Arming codes?
What the hell for?

1488
01:30:21,920 --> 01:30:24,720
Mitch, we can do or we can teach.
What's your pleasure?

1489
01:30:24,799 --> 01:30:26,159
[Sighs]

1490
01:30:26,240 --> 01:30:28,880
Get the arming codes!
Get the goddam codes!

1491
01:30:28,960 --> 01:30:31,119
We have one helicopter.
Holds 7 people.

1492
01:30:31,200 --> 01:30:33,640
We can ferry 6 people to
high ground in West Virginia

1493
01:30:33,760 --> 01:30:34,640
and take Jenny to the ARK.

1494
01:30:34,720 --> 01:30:37,241
Short stick goes.

1495
01:30:37,361 --> 01:30:39,240
I thought it was women
and children first.

1496
01:30:39,360 --> 01:30:41,081
If you get the short one,
you can give up your seat.

